    <description>
        <div>
            <p>A Federal appropriations act for the year ending Jun 30, 1875 (Jun 20, 1874; 18 Stat.
                90), authorized the President to appoint a Third Assistant Secretary of State. The
                Secretary of State was authorized to prescribe the duties of the Assistant
                Secretaries and other Department of State employees, “and may make changes and
                transfers therein when, in his judgment, it becomes necessary.” The Third Assistant
                Secretary’s duties varied over the years, including such diverse assignments as:
                supervision of several geographic divisions; oversight of the Bureaus of Accounts
                and Appointments; international conferences and commissions; and ceremonials and
                protocol, including presentation to the President of chiefs of foreign diplomatic
                missions. The Foreign Service Act of 1924 (May 24, 1924; 43 Stat 146) abolished
                numerical titles for Assistant Secretaries of State.</p>
        </div>
    </description>
